Based on my search, here's how to use the Slack `chat.update` API to modify a message after a button click in TypeScript:

## Overview

"By using chat.update and your created message's message_ts field, you can modify the original interactive message (including all of its attachments) to add or remove buttons or menus based on user interactions."

## Key Requirements

### API Method: `chat.update`

The `chat.update` method updates a message. It requires the channel containing the message to be updated and the timestamp of the message to be updated.(no content)New Slack apps may use this method with the `chat:write` scope and either a bot or user token.

### Important Considerations

Ephemeral messages can't be updated this way. An app can't update every message in a conversation - only ones posted by the authenticated user of the token being used, including those posted as the app.(no content)Bot users may also update the messages they post. Attempting to update other message types will return a `cant_update_message` error. To use `chat.update` with a bot user's token, you'll need to pass `as_user` set to `true` while editing a message created by that same bot user.

### Block Kit Behavior

To remove previous blocks, include an empty array for the blocks field. If blocks are used and a message is being updated, the edited flag will not be displayed on the message.(no content)If you don't include blocks, the message's previous blocks will only be retained if the text argument is not provided. If the text argument is provided and blocks are not provided, the blocks will be removed.

## TypeScript Example Pattern

Using the Node Slack SDK with TypeScript:

```typescript
import { WebClient, LogLevel } from "@slack/web-api";

const client = new WebClient("xoxb-your-token", {
  logLevel: LogLevel.DEBUG
});

// In your button action handler:
app.action("button_action_id", async ({ body, ack, client }) => {
  await ack();

  // Update the message
  await client.chat.update({
    channel: body.channel.id,
    ts: body.message.ts,  // The timestamp of the original message
    text: "Message updated after button click",
    blocks: [
      {
        type: "section",
        text: {
          type: "mrkdwn",
          text: "✅ Action completed!"
        }
      }
    ]
  });
});
```

## Handling Button Click Payloads

When a user clicks on a button, your server will be sent a URL encoded request containing a body parameter called payload. The payload is itself a URL encoded JSON string so use `JSON.parse()` to extract the desired data.

The payload includes `message_ts` (the original message timestamp) and `response_url` which you can use to respond.

## Interactive Message Flow

Set `completed` to `false` in order to keep the interactivity points (the approve/deny buttons) "alive". You will set the function's complete state in the button handlers below.


REMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks.

