Excellent! Now I have all the information needed. Let me compile the comprehensive response with specific examples.

## Summary

I've completed comprehensive research on Slack Block Kit for building interactive QA assignment messages. Here are the key findings with practical JSON and TypeScript examples.

---

## 1. Block Kit Structure for QA Assignment Messages

### Message with Text + Buttons

Here's the complete block structure for a QA assignment message:

```json
{
  "blocks": [
    {
      "type": "section",
      "text": {
        "type": "mrkdwn",
        "text": "*QA Assignment - Bug Fix Required*"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "section",
      "fields": [
        {
          "type": "mrkdwn",
          "text": "*Ticket ID:*\nQA-2847"
        },
        {
          "type": "mrkdwn",
          "text": "*Priority:*\n🔴 High"
        },
        {
          "type": "mrkdwn",
          "text": "*Title:*\nLogin form validation not working"
        },
        {
          "type": "mrkdwn",
          "text": "*Assignee:*\n<@U12345678>"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "section",
      "text": {
        "type": "mrkdwn",
        "text": "*Description:*\nUsers unable to submit login form with special characters in password field. Affects ~15% of users on Chrome browser."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "divider"
    },
    {
      "type": "actions",
      "block_id": "qa_assignment_actions",
      "elements": [
        {
          "type": "button",
          "text": {
            "type": "plain_text",
            "text": "Claim",
            "emoji": true
          },
          "value": "qa-2847-claim",
          "action_id": "qa_claim_button",
          "style": "primary"
        },
        {
          "type": "button",
          "text": {
            "type": "plain_text",
            "text": "Pass",
            "emoji": true
          },
          "value": "qa-2847-pass",
          "action_id": "qa_pass_button"
        },
        {
          "type": "button",
          "text": {
            "type": "plain_text",
            "text": "Blocked",
            "emoji": true
          },
          "value": "qa-2847-blocked",
          "action_id": "qa_blocked_button",
          "style": "danger"
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```

**Key Components:**
- **Section Block**: Display title and description text
- **Fields**: Show structured ticket info in a grid format
- **Actions Block**: Container for interactive buttons
- **Divider**: Visual separator

---

## 2. Interactive Buttons: action_id and block_id Pattern

### Button Definition Pattern

```json
{
  "type": "button",
  "text": {
    "type": "plain_text",
    "text": "Button Label",
    "emoji": true
  },
  "value": "unique-value-123",      // Data sent in payload
  "action_id": "button_action_id",  // Identifies the button
  "style": "primary",                // "primary" (green) or "danger" (red)
  "confirm": {                       // Optional confirmation dialog
    "title": { "type": "plain_text", "text": "Confirm?" },
    "text": { "type": "mrkdwn", "text": "Are you sure?" },
    "confirm_text": { "type": "plain_text", "text": "Yes" },
    "deny_text": { "type": "plain_text", "text": "No" }
  }
}
```

### Naming Convention Best Practice

For your QA assignment system:
```
action_id: "qa_{action}_button"  // e.g., qa_claim_button
block_id:  "qa_assignment_actions"
value:     "{ticket_id}-{action}" // e.g., QA-2847-claim
```

---

## 3. Button Click Payload Structure

### Complete block_actions Payload

When a user clicks a button, Slack sends this payload to your Request URL:

```json
{
  "type": "block_actions",
  "user": {
    "id": "U12345678",
    "username": "sarah.johnson",
    "name": "Sarah Johnson",
    "team_id": "T987654321"
  },
  "api_app_id": "A11111111",
  "token": "verification_token",
  "container": {
    "type": "message",
    "message_ts": "1609459200.001200"
  },
  "trigger_id": "1234567890.1234567890.abcdefgh",
  "team": {
    "id": "T987654321",
    "domain": "my-workspace"
  },
  "enterprise": null,
  "is_enterprise_install": false,
  "channel": {
    "id": "C11111111",
    "name": "qa-assignments"
  },
  "message": {
    "type": "message",
    "user": "USLACKBOT",
    "ts": "1609459200.001200",
    "bot_id": "B11111111",
    "app_id": "A11111111",
    "text": "QA Assignment",
    "blocks": [/* ... original blocks ... */]
  },
  "view": null,
  "state": null,
  "response_url": "https://hooks.slack.com/actions/T987654321/...",
  "actions": [
    {
      "type": "button",
      "action_id": "qa_claim_button",
      "block_id": "qa_assignment_actions",
      "text": {
        "type": "plain_text",
        "text": "Claim",
        "emoji": true
      },
      "value": "QA-2847-claim",
      "style": "primary",
      "action_ts": "1609459234.123456"
    }
  ]
}
```

**Key Fields for Your Handler:**
- `actions[0].action_id` - Identifies which button was clicked
- `actions[0].value` - Your custom data (ticket ID + action)
- `user.id` - Who clicked the button
- `channel.id` - Where the message was posted
- `message.ts` - Timestamp to update the message later
- `trigger_id` - For opening modals as follow-up

---

## 4. Button Callback Handling

### Endpoint Setup & Request Verification

**Step 1: Get Raw Request Body (Express.js)**

```typescript
import express from 'express';
import crypto from 'crypto';

const app = express();

// Capture raw body for signature verification
app.use(
  express.urlencoded({
    extended: true,
    verify: (req, _, buf) => {
      req.rawBody = buf.toString('utf-8');
    },
  })
);
```

**Step 2: Verify Slack Signature**

```typescript
interface SlackRequest {
  rawBody: string;
  headers: {
    'x-slack-signature'?: string;
    'x-slack-request-timestamp'?: string;
  };
}

function verifySlackSignature(
  req: SlackRequest,
  signingSecret: string
): boolean {
  const timestamp = req.headers['x-slack-request-timestamp'];
  const signature = req.headers['x-slack-signature'];

  // Check if timestamp is within 5 minutes (prevent replay attacks)
  const currentTime = Math.floor(Date.now() / 1000);
  if (Math.abs(currentTime - parseInt(timestamp!)) > 300) {
    console.error('Timestamp too old - possible replay attack');
    return false;
  }

  // Construct the base string: v0:timestamp:body
  const baseString = `v0:${timestamp}:${req.rawBody}`;

  // Generate signature using HMAC-SHA256
  const computed = crypto
    .createHmac('sha256', signingSecret)
    .update(baseString)
    .digest('hex');

  const computedSignature = `v0=${computed}`;

  // Use timing-safe comparison to prevent timing attacks
  return crypto.timingSafeEqual(
    Buffer.from(signature!),
    Buffer.from(computedSignature)
  );
}
```

**Step 3: Handle Button Click & Respond**

```typescript
import { WebClient } from '@slack/web-api';

const slackClient = new WebClient(process.env.SLACK_BOT_TOKEN);

interface BlockActionsPayload {
  type: string;
  user: { id: string; username: string };
  channel: { id: string; name: string };
  message: { ts: string };
  actions: Array<{
    action_id: string;
    block_id: string;
    value: string;
    type: string;
    action_ts: string;
  }>;
  response_url: string;
  trigger_id: string;
}

app.post('/slack/interactive', async (req, res) => {
  // Verify signature
  if (!verifySlackSignature(req, process.env.SLACK_SIGNING_SECRET!)) {
    return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Unauthorized' });
  }

  try {
    // Parse payload
    const payload = JSON.parse(req.body.payload) as BlockActionsPayload;

    // **IMPORTANT: Acknowledge immediately within 3 seconds**
    res.status(200).json({});

    // Get action details
    const action = payload.actions[0];
    const [ticketId, actionType] = action.value.split('-');
    const userId = payload.user.id;
    const timestamp = new Date().toISOString();

    // Handle based on action_id
    switch (action.action_id) {
      case 'qa_claim_button':
        await handleQAClaim(ticketId, userId, payload);
        break;
      case 'qa_pass_button':
        await handleQAPass(ticketId, userId, payload);
        break;
      case 'qa_blocked_button':
        await handleQABlocked(ticketId, userId, payload);
        break;
    }
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Error handling interaction:', error);
    res.status(500).json({ error: 'Internal server error' });
  }
});
```

---

## 5. Update Message After Button Click

### Best Practice: Show Who Clicked and When

```typescript
async function handleQAClaim(
  ticketId: string,
  userId: string,
  payload: BlockActionsPayload
) {
  const timestamp = Math.floor(Date.now() / 1000);
  const userMention = `<@${userId}>`;

  try {
    // Update the original message
    await slackClient.chat.update({
      channel: payload.channel.id,
      ts: payload.message.ts,
      text: `QA Assignment ${ticketId} - Claimed by ${userMention}`,
      blocks: [
        {
          type: "section",
          text: {
            type: "mrkdwn",
            text: `*QA Assignment - ${ticketId}*\n✅ Claimed by ${userMention}`
          }
        },
        {
          type: "context",
          elements: [
            {
              type: "mrkdwn",
              text: `Claimed <!date^${timestamp}^at {time} on {date}|just now> by ${userMention}`
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    });

    // Optional: Send a confirmation to the user
    await slackClient.chat.postEphemeral({
      channel: payload.channel.id,
      user: userId,
      text: `You claimed ${ticketId}`,
      blocks: [
        {
          type: "section",
          text: {
            type: "mrkdwn",
            text: `✅ You successfully claimed *${ticketId}*\n\nYou can now start working on this QA assignment.`
          }
        }
      ]
    });

  } catch (error) {
    console.error(`Failed to claim ${ticketId}:`, error);
  }
}

async function handleQAPass(
  ticketId: string,
  userId: string,
  payload: BlockActionsPayload
) {
  const timestamp = Math.floor(Date.now() / 1000);

  await slackClient.chat.update({
    channel: payload.channel.id,
    ts: payload.message.ts,
    text: `QA Assignment ${ticketId} - Passed by <@${userId}>`,
    blocks: [
      {
        type: "section",
        text: {
          type: "mrkdwn",
          text: `*QA Assignment - ${ticketId}*\n✅ Status: Passed`
        }
      },
      {
        type: "context",
        elements: [
          {
            type: "mrkdwn",
            text: `Passed by <@${userId}> <!date^${timestamp}^at {time} on {date}|just now>`
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  });
}

async function handleQABlocked(
  ticketId: string,
  userId: string,
  payload: BlockActionsPayload
) {
  const timestamp = Math.floor(Date.now() / 1000);

  // For blocked, you might open a modal to get a reason
  await slackClient.views.open({
    trigger_id: payload.trigger_id,
    view: {
      type: "modal",
      callback_id: `blocked_reason_${ticketId}`,
      title: { type: "plain_text", text: "QA Blocked" },
      blocks: [
        {
          type: "section",
          text: {
            type: "mrkdwn",
            text: `Why is *${ticketId}* blocked?`
          }
        },
        {
          type: "input",
          block_id: "reason_block",
          label: { type: "plain_text", text: "Reason" },
          element: {
            type: "plain_text_input",
            action_id: "reason_input",
            multiline: true,
            placeholder: { type: "plain_text", text: "Waiting for deployment, missing requirements, etc." }
          }
        }
      ],
      submit: { type: "plain_text", text: "Submit" }
    }
  });
}
```

---

## 6. Best Practices for QA Assignment Messages

### 1. **Signature Verification (CRITICAL)**

Always verify signatures with timing-safe comparison to prevent timing attacks. Use the exact base string format: `v0:timestamp:body`

### 2. **Message Updates Best Practice**

```typescript
// Good: Replace interactive blocks with confirmation
await client.chat.update({
  channel,
  ts: message.ts,
  blocks: [
    // Show result
    { type: "section", text: { type: "mrkdwn", text: "✅ Claimed!" } },
    // Show who and when
    { type: "context", elements: [...] }
    // Remove old buttons
  ]
});

// Don't: Leave buttons visible after interaction
// Users may click again, causing duplicate actions
```

### 3. **Three-Second Acknowledgment**

Always respond with HTTP 200 within 3 seconds of receiving the payload:

```typescript
res.status(200).json({}); // Immediate acknowledgment
// Then handle the action asynchronously
```

### 4. **Context Blocks for Metadata**

```json
{
  "type": "context",
  "elements": [
    {
      "type": "mrkdwn",
      "text": "Last action: Claimed by <@U12345> <!date^1609459234^at {time}|15 minutes ago>"
    }
  ]
}
```

### 5. **Use Styling for Visual Hierarchy**

```json
{
  "type": "button",
  "style": "primary",    // Green - for positive actions (Claim, Approve)
  "text": { "type": "plain_text", "text": "Claim" }
}

{
  "type": "button",
  "style": "danger",     // Red - for destructive actions (Blocked)
  "text": { "type": "plain_text", "text": "Blocked" }
}
```

---

## Summary Table

| Component | Key Points |
|-----------|-----------|
| **Blocks** | Use sections for info, actions for buttons, divider for spacing |
| **Button ID** | `action_id` identifies button; `value` contains data payload |
| **Payload** | Contains `actions[0]` with `action_id`, `block_id`, `value`, `user` |
| **Verification** | HMAC-SHA256 base string: `v0:{timestamp}:{body}` |
| **Response** | Acknowledge within 3 seconds, then update message async |
| **Updates** | Use `chat.update` with `channel.id` and `message.ts` |
| **Context** | Show who acted and when using `context` blocks |

---

